  "texts": [
    "It is known that there cannot be an algorithm with polynomial time for an NP-hard problem, unless P = NP.",
    "The field of theoretical computer science usually assumes that P ≠ NP holds, and there exists a Millennium prize to prove or disprove this.",
    "But even if P = NP, it is assumed that the exponent in the running time of any polynomial time algorithm will be prohibitively high, and the resulting algorithms will be of no practical use, similar to the polynomial-time algorithm for PRIMES 59.",
    "To compute distances for our UMAP embedding in Fig. 3 required to swiftly solve more than 160 million instances of the NP-hard MCES problem.",
    "We present an efficient implementation based on computing lower distance bounds to quickly recognize dissimilar structure pairs, with an additional step for potentially similar pairs for which we compute provably exact distances with an Integer Linear Programming (ILP) formulation."
  ],
